content: OK guys I don't even wanna make beats now.. I've tried since that stupid update.. am I the only one that hates what y'all did. plus my patterns do not save now.. replyContent: Google forces with Android Q/R all apps to use the "System Files Picker" in order to access files on the shared storage. If you want to use it as you did in the old version, simply move your folder '/sdcard/gstomper' to '/sdcard/Android/data/com.planeth.gstomper/files/gstomper'. Once you did that, everything will work exactly as in the old versions

Bought the app on impulse last night and I like it a lot. The drum 
machine/step sequencer is good fun and the synth is deeper than I expected. 
The presets are nice too. The only issue I have is that I need to have a 
perfect mix before I duplicate my first pattern, as all perameter changes 
(both in the mixer and on the sounds themselves) are per pattern. It would 
be great if there was a global edit mode, where you could tweak the sounds 
and mix across all patterns (with automated parameters greyed out perhaps) 
instead of having to repeat the changes in each pattern. What if you plug 
into a big system and decide the kick is too loud?
replyContent: Thanks a lot for your feedback, Django. Having "global mixer settings" is on the task list (will be similar to the "master lock"). content: The best music development app on android keeps getting better. This isn't as well known as Caustic or FL Studio, and it is expensive for an app, but you get an astonishing level of musical functionality for your cash. Prepare to scratch your head a bit, because complex music requires a bit of effort on your part. But the results can be just brilliant, and comparable with desktop DAWs. Best parts are conditional events in the step sequencer, which can make simple loops change in musical ways, the wonderful flexibility of the Beast synth, midi mapping that puts many PC based DAWs to shame, and continued development which actually makes the app better in really useful ways, rather than just making it work with the latest android version. Recently added: midi file import, and midi profile loading and saving. :-D

content: I'm disappointed in this app. $12 and I can't even set my sounds to Monophony. It doesn't even work in the setup menu. I hope I'm just missing something. The app is great for what it is but with the inability to cut off sounds it makes it not worth it.
replyContent:
App wide Drum Sampler Monophony = Main Screen / SETUP / SMP / Sampler Monophony.
Per Track Drum Sampler Monophony = Long press a Track (e.g. T01, then enable a Mute Group, then long press the Mute Group to activate its monophony extension.
A Mute Group works with 1-n members.
And there's more. Please mail us: Main Menu / Help / Contact developer

content: After 4 months with this app I'm convinced it's the best available on Android for my workflow.  The GUI is intuitive after a short learning curve and the control I have over everything is expansive yet not overwhelming.  Having only started using DAWs this year I'm at a point now with this app that it can do everything I can dream up and more.  One of the draw-backs (and this is down to personal preference) is the pattern-based work flow isn't the ideal way for me to plan and organize a piece of work.  There is a lot of flexibility within each pattern to create crazy time signatures (which is a huge plus compared to the competition) but I need to visualize a song as a whole to really get it structured properly.  There are other apps out there which are organized differently (FL Studio for example) and I prefer that setup but I always come back to G-Stomper because it's just so much more flexible and awesome in every other way that I'm learning to work around my personal preferences.    If you want to compose music with a great DAW on android this is the app to get.
replyContent: Thank you very much, Tim, for your detailed review. Your feedback is really appreciated. It would be great to get into some deeper discussion about the song composer. Just feel free to contact us (Main Menu / Help / Contact Developer)

content: Today I'm having a weird problem where some of my synths don't play when I transition to their pattern. When it loops around, or I play the pattern on its own they work fine. It's super weird.
replyContent: Thanks for your feedback, Joe. When you switch to another pattern, then you actually change everything, drum samples, synth presets, fx, etc. This means, if a synth overlaps a pattern change, it'll probably sound different in the new pattern. To avoid that behavior, make sure that you have exactly the same synth sounds loaded in the new pattern.

content: No, not five stars but close. First, I am using a Samsung T800 10.5" and this tablet easily handles the load. The tablet screen adds some latency and I'll deal with that later. As an overall sequencer and sound machine, for the price and the fact that we're using a tab here, this is one of the best that I've seen. The Devs have thought of and packed everything you could need into this app and I think it's a shame that we have to call this just an "app". I won't go into details because if you're interested in this app you're serious and knowledgeable enough about the toys included, save to say that there's a bit of a learning curve here but the tools are familiar. I took off a star because as a engineer, and a musician, I reserve the right to get pissy about details. I bought some of the sound packs because, face it, the Devs worked hard enough on the "studio", there isn't a whole lot of sounds included. Watch out for the sound packs, while they are cheap, the drum packs, some of them anyway, are rotten old dm mch sounds and very cheap sounding at that. I expected more from the separate sound packs. I'll use my own from now on. So! Four stars for one of the best andriod seq/samplrs
replyContent: Thank you very much for your detailed review, Dave. Please leave a message at http://www.planet-h.com/contact-us/ with a list of the packs you bought. I'm sure I can give you something you'll be very happy with in exchange.

content: In the pictures it shows the piano roll and other stuff I can't seem to access. Is G-stomper 2 still available or is it becoming a update soon?
replyContent: Click on 'Select View' and choose the view you want to open. The piano roll is located on the 'Note Grid'. Or you can use the step buttons on the main screen as piano roll, when the note edit mode is enabled. G-Stomper 2 is of course still available and will be in the future. It get's updated periodicly, but these updates are free of charge.

This is undoubtedly the best production app for Android. The range of control and scope that this has is unrivaled. It is entirely feasible to make entire tracks with this and the new Note Grid allows for better control when adding basslines and creating arps/runs/melodies. Depending upon your needs this can act as a beat creator, a sequencer or a sample manipulator. One thing that is very impressive but doesn't seem to be mentioned on the descfription is the on the spot timestretching that occurs when you load a loop into a slot - it just does it without fuss and without fail everytime.

There really isn't anything I can't do with g stomper, if I can think it, its doable. Not only do I use it for drum beats but also for melodies, great app to mix up samples to create unique sounds.  I have two new ideas:   1. Auto save feature, a temp file created at shutdown of the app. Then at next startup it should check for the temp file and ask if you want it loaded.  2. When changing the note, I noticed that the notes after the one you change, become the same note. Though I have not read the entire manual, and I could be missing something.  All and all great app, great developer, and great fun. Don't waste your money on electrum, cadeli, etc, they just get neglected.
